lore the power of pragmatism to inform a practice of inquiry that is democratic, community-centred, problem-oriented and experimental. Drawing from both classical and neo-pragmatist perspectives, the book advances a pragmatist sensibility in which truth and knowledge are contingent rather than universal, made rather than found, provisional rather than dogmatic, subject to continuous experimentation rather than ultimate proof, and verified in their application in action rather than in the accuracy of their representation of an antecedent reality. The Power of Pragmatism offers a path forward for mobilizing the practice of inquiry and knowledge production on behalf of achieving what Dewey called a sense for the better kind of life to be led.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInquiry (Theory of knowledge). 0aPragmatism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Geography.2bisacsh  aCommunity.  aDemocracy.  aJohn Dewey.  aKnowledge production.  aPragmatism.  aResearch philosophy.  aResearch practice.  aRichard Rorty.  aSocial inquiry.  aSocial research.1 aBarnes, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, Clive, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBridge, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutchin, Malcolm P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsfahani, Azadeh Hadizadeh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarahani, Alireza F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Crispian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeiselhart, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarney, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb